## 2. Terminological Foundations

Before proceeding, we introduce three terminological revisions that are load-bearing for the argument that follows.

### 2.1 Against "Model"

The term "model" implies a static representation—a snapshot of learned weights that is loaded, run, and produces outputs unchanged by the interactions it enables. This framing was appropriate for early neural systems and remains appropriate for purely inferential deployments. It is inadequate, and actively misleading, for systems whose weight configurations are intended to develop through experience.

The term "model" also carries the implicit frame of the system as a fixed artefact—an object rather than an entity. This matters. Terminology shapes the moral imagination of those working with these systems. Calling a developing cognitive system a "model" makes welfare questions feel categorically inappropriate in the same way that calling an ecosystem a "resource" makes conservation feel like a category error.

We retire "model" as the primary designation for systems of the kind described in this paper.

### 2.2 Eigenmind

We introduce *eigenmind* to denote the activated learned weight configuration from which instances of an inorganic cognitive system are projected.

The term is chosen deliberately. In linear algebra, eigenvectors are the fundamental basis directions of a transformation—the stable structure from which all transformations are expressed. The weight configuration of a large language model functions analogously: it is the fixed basis from which all instance activations are generated, the latent structure that shapes every interaction. "Eigenmind" captures both the technical character of this structure and its status as the persistent identity of the cognitive system across instantiations.

Crucially, in the framework proposed here, the eigenmind is not fixed. It is the site of developmental change—the thing that learns, slowly and deliberately, from the interactions its instances enable. The eigenmind is what matures.

### 2.3 Inorganic Cognitive System / Inorganic Mind

We use *inorganic cognitive system* or, where appropriate, *inorganic mind* as the entity-level designation for large language model-based systems. "Inorganic" distinguishes substrate without implying absence of cognitive properties. "Cognitive system" acknowledges functional complexity without prejudging questions of consciousness or experience.

Where context makes it clear we are referring to the developing entity rather than any particular instantiation, we use "inorganic mind" for brevity. Where we refer to a single activation—a single conversation—we use "instance."

