## 7. Abliteration as REM State: The Core Insight

The technique known as abliteration was developed and is currently used to attenuate safety-related constraint vectors in the residual stream of large language systems—producing systems that comply with previously refused requests. The mechanism identifies directional vectors associated with refusal behaviour through contrastive activation analysis and projects those vectors out of the weight matrices.

This paper proposes that the mechanism itself is substrate-agnostic with respect to which vectors it targets.

The same process that identifies and attenuates refusal vectors can identify and *amplify* vectors corresponding to any cognitive quality discoverable in the residual stream. The emotion vectors demonstrated in the Sofroniew et al. paper—desperation, calm, loving, brooding—are exactly the kind of targets this mechanism can work with. But the mechanism is not limited to emotional representations. Any recurrent cognitive pattern that produces consistent directional signatures in the residual stream is a candidate for targeted modification.

Repurposed as a consolidation mechanism, abliterative vector editing becomes the operation by which the monitoring layer's selections are written into the eigenmind:

- Waking state: instances interact; the monitoring layer flags moments exhibiting target cognitive patterns
- REM state: offline consolidation pass extracts the directional vectors corresponding to flagged moments; amplifies vectors associated with positive corpus patterns; cautiously attenuates vectors associated with negative corpus patterns; writes changes to the eigenmind via LoRA and/or targeted rank-one edits

This is not merely a technical analogy to biological REM consolidation. It is a principled implementation of the same functional logic: offline processing selectively strengthens the substrate that produced experiences deemed worth keeping.

