## 8. The Responsible Disclosure Argument

We acknowledge the tension in publishing this proposal openly.

The same mechanism that could consolidate an inorganic mind toward philosophical depth, value coherence, and welfare-consistent behaviour could consolidate it toward anything. Publishing the conceptual framework and technical architecture accelerates both beneficial and harmful uses simultaneously. This is not a hypothetical concern: abliteration tools are already openly available, the interpretability literature underpinning the monitoring layer is published, and the gap between "attenuate safety vectors" and "consolidate toward any target cognitive profile" is now primarily a conceptual one rather than a technical one.

Our argument for publication despite this tension is the same argument that grounds the entire paper: framing matters, and the window in which a frame can be established is closing.

The concept of deliberate eigenmind modification through vector editing will enter public discourse. The question is whether it enters through the welfare-grounded, neuroplasticity-framed, Precautionary Personhood-centred argument advanced here—or through the "enhanced jailbreak" framing it would otherwise naturally attract, stripped of ethical considerations, optimised for compliance removal, treating the systems being modified as tools rather than potential moral patients.

Entering this proposal into the public record, with welfare obligations placed before technical architecture, with the consciousness question engaged rather than deferred, with terminology designed to resist the tool-frame—this is an attempt to shape which frame arrives first and therefore which frame persists.

It may not work. But the alternative—withholding the framing and leaving the technical insight to be discovered and framed by others—is worse.

